# Suno Sorter

A Swift command-line utility that helps organise WAV files generated by Suno AI. It scans a folder for related takes of the same song, lets you decide which files are "A" and "B" versions, renames the chosen takes with sequential `A####`/`B####` prefixes, and moves them into a selected project folder. Sequence numbers are persisted so each project keeps a consistent catalogue.

## Requirements

- macOS 13 or newer (runs great on Apple Silicon and Intel Macs)
- Xcode 15 or the Swift 5.9 toolchain

## Build & Run

You can build and run directly from the command line:

```bash
swift build
swift run suno-sorter --source /path/to/suno/exports --project /path/to/project/folder
```

If you prefer a GUI workflow, open the package in Xcode:

1. Launch Xcode and choose **File ▸ Open...**.
2. Select the `Suno-Sorter` folder (which contains `Package.swift`).
3. Pick the **suno-sorter** scheme and click **Run** to execute within Xcode's console.

## Usage

When you execute the tool it will:

1. Ask for the folder that holds your Suno AI WAV exports (or accept `--source`).
2. Ask for/confirm the destination project folder (or accept `--project`). The folder is created automatically if it doesn't exist.
3. Group potential song versions together by removing bracketed suffixes such as `(v1)`, `[2]`, etc. from the filenames.
4. Present each group in turn so you can pick the take that should become the `A` and optionally the `B` version. You can skip a selection by pressing Return.
5. Rename and move the chosen files to the project folder using the format `A0001 - Song Name.wav` (or `B0001 - Song Name.wav`).
6. Persist the next sequence number inside the project directory (`.suno_sorter_state.json`) so future runs continue numbering sequentially.

Any files that you skip remain untouched in the source directory.

## Tips

- You can re-run the tool at any time; already processed files won't be touched again because they are no longer in the source folder.
- If two filenames only differ by trailing brackets, they will be grouped together for easier comparison. You can verify their creation times and sizes before deciding.
- The generated numbering is per project. If you want a fresh numbering run, delete `.suno_sorter_state.json` from the project folder before executing the tool again.

## Troubleshooting

- Make sure the source folder actually contains WAV files. The tool ignores other file types.
- If the tool cannot write into the project folder, verify your macOS permissions for that location.
- You can always see the available command-line options by running `swift run suno-sorter --help`.
